[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Asynchronously reads the entire contents of a file.If no encoding is specified (using `options.encoding`), the data is returned as a `<Buffer>` object.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Otherwise, the data will be a string.If `options` is a string, then it specifies the encoding.If `buffer` is provided and no encoding is specified, the returned `<Buffer>` is a view over the supplied buffer containing only the bytes read.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the supplied buffer is too small to contain the entire file, the promise will be rejected.When the `path` is a directory, the behavior of `fsPromises.readFile()` is platform-specific.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] On macOS, Linux, and Windows, the promise will be rejected with an error.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Reads the contents of the symbolic link referred to by `path`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] See the POSIX `readlink(2)` documentation for more detail.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The promise is fulfilled with the `linkString` upon success.The optional `options` argument can be a string specifying an encoding, or an object with an `encoding` property specifying the character encoding to use for the link path returned.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the `encoding` is set to `'buffer'`, the link path returned will be passed as a `<Buffer>` object.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the `encoding` is set to `'buffer'`, the path returned will be passed as a `<Buffer>` object.On Linux, when Node.js is linked against musl libc, the procfs file system must be mounted on `/proc` in order for this function to work.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Removes files and directories (modeled on the standard POSIX `rm` utility).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Creates a symbolic link.The `type` argument is only used on Windows platforms and can be one of `'dir'`, `'file'`, or `'junction'`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the `type` argument is `null`, Node.js will autodetect `target` type and use `'file'` or `'dir'`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the `target` does not exist, `'file'` will be used.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Windows junction points require the destination path to be absolute.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] When using `'junction'`, the `target` argument will automatically be normalized to absolute path.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Junction points on NTFS volumes can only point to directories.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Truncates (shortens or extends the length) of the content at `path` to `len` bytes.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If `path` refers to a symbolic link, then the link is removed without affecting the file or directory to which that link refers.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the `path` refers to a file path that is not a symbolic link, the file is deleted.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] See the POSIX `unlink(2)` documentation for more detail.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Change the file system timestamps of the object referenced by `path`.The `atime` and `mtime` arguments follow these rules: Values can be either numbers representing Unix epoch time, `Date`s, or a numeric string like `'123456789.0'`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the value can not be converted to a number, or is `NaN`, `Infinity`, or `-Infinity`, an `Error` will be thrown.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `data` can be a string, a buffer, an `<AsyncIterable>`, or an {Iterable} object.The `encoding` option is ignored if `data` is a buffer.If `options` is a string, then it specifies the encoding.The `mode` option only affects the newly created file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] For performance sensitive code consider using `fs.createWriteStream()` or `filehandle.createWriteStream()`.It is possible to use an `<AbortSignal>` to cancel an `fsPromises.writeFile()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Returns an object containing commonly used constants for file system operations.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The object is the same as `fs.constants`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The callback APIs perform all operations asynchronously, without blocking the event loop, then invoke a callback function upon completion or error.The callback APIs use the underlying Node.js threadpool to perform file system operations off the event loop thread.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Check File access constants for possible values of `mode`.The final argument, `callback`, is a callback function that is invoked with a possible error argument.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If any of the accessibility checks fail, the error argument will be an `Error` object.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The following examples check if `package.json` exists, and if it is readable or writable.import { access, constants } from 'node:fs'; const file = 'package.json'; // Check if the file exists in the current directory. access(file, constants.F_OK, (err) => { console.log(`${file} ${err ?
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] 'does not exist' : 'exists'}`); }); // Check if the file is readable. access(file, constants.R_OK, (err) => { console.log(`${file} ${err ?
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] 'is not readable' : 'is readable'}`); }); // Check if the file is writable. access(file, constants.W_OK, (err) => { console.log(`${file} ${err ?
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] 'is not writable' : 'is writable'}`); }); // Check if the file is readable and writable. access(file, constants.R_OK | constants.W_OK, (err) => { console.log(`${file} ${err ?
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] 'is not' : 'is'} readable and writable`); });Do not use `fs.access()` to check for the accessibility of a file before calling `fs.open()`, `fs.readFile()`, or `fs.writeFile()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `fs.access()` function, however, does not check the ACL and therefore may report that a path is accessible even if the ACL restricts the user from reading or writing to it.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `data` can be a string or a `<Buffer>`.The `mode` option only affects the newly created file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Asynchronously changes the permissions of a file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The left-most digit (`7` in the example), specifies the permissions for the file owner.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The middle digit (`6` in the example), specifies permissions for the group.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The right-most digit (`5` in the example), specifies the permissions for others.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Number Description `7` read, write, and execute `6` read and write `5` read and execute `4` read only `3` write and execute `2` write only `1` execute only `0` no permission For example, the octal value `0o765` means: The owner may read, write, and execute the file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] When using raw numbers where file modes are expected, any value larger than `0o777` may result in platform-specific behaviors that are not supported to work consistently.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Therefore constants like `S_ISVTX`, `S_ISGID`, or `S_ISUID` are not exposed in `fs.constants`.Caveats: on Windows only the write permission can be changed, and the distinction among the permissions of group, owner, or others is not implemented.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Asynchronously changes owner and group of a file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] No arguments other than a possible exception are given to the completion callback.See the POSIX `chown(2)` documentation for more detail.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] No arguments other than a possible exception are given to the completion callback.Calling `fs.close()` on any file descriptor (`fd`) that is currently in use through any other `fs` operation may lead to undefined behavior.See the POSIX `close(2)` documentation for more detail.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] By default, `dest` is overwritten if it already exists.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] No arguments other than a possible exception are given to the callback function.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Node.js makes no guarantees about the atomicity of the copy operation.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If an error occurs after the destination file has been opened for writing, Node.js will attempt to remove the destination.`mode` is an optional integer that specifies the behavior of the copy operation.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] It is possible to create a mask consisting of the bitwise OR of two or more values (e.g.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `fs.constants.COPYFILE_EXCL | fs.constants.COPYFILE_FICLONE`).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `fs.constants.COPYFILE_EXCL`: The copy operation will fail if `dest` already exists.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `fs.constants.COPYFILE_FICLONE`: The copy operation will attempt to create a copy-on-write reflink.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the platform does not support copy-on-write, then a fallback copy mechanism is used.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `fs.constants.COPYFILE_FICLONE_FORCE`: The copy operation will attempt to create a copy-on-write reflink.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the platform does not support copy-on-write, then the operation will fail.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If `fd` is specified and `start` is omitted or `undefined`, `fs.createReadStream()` reads sequentially from the current file position.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `encoding` can be any one of those accepted by `<Buffer>`.If `fd` is specified, `ReadStream` will ignore the `path` argument and will use the specified file descriptor.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] This means that no `'open'` event will be emitted.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `fd` should be blocking; non-blocking `fd`s should be passed to `<net.Socket>`.If `fd` points to a character device that only supports blocking reads (such as keyboard or sound card), read operations do not finish until data is available.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Set the `emitClose` option to `false` to change this behavior.By providing the `fs` option, it is possible to override the corresponding `fs` implementations for `open`, `read`, and `close`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] When providing the `fs` option, an override for `read` is required.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If no `fd` is provided, an override for `open` is also required.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Modifying a file rather than replacing it may require the `flags` option to be set to `r+` rather than the default `w`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Set the `emitClose` option to `false` to change this behavior.By providing the `fs` option it is possible to override the corresponding `fs` implementations for `open`, `write`, `writev`, and `close`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Overriding `write()` without `writev()` can reduce performance as some optimizations (`_writev()`) will be disabled.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] When providing the `fs` option, overrides for at least one of `write` and `writev` are required.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If no `fd` option is supplied, an override for `open` is also required.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If `autoClose` is `true`, an override for `close` is also required.Like `<fs.ReadStream>`, if `fd` is specified, `<fs.WriteStream>` will ignore the `path` argument and will use the specified file descriptor.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `fd` should be blocking; non-blocking `fd`s should be passed to `<net.Socket>`.If `options` is a string, then it specifies the encoding.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Stability: 0 - Deprecated: Use `fs.stat()` or `fs.access()` instead.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Test whether or not the element at the given `path` exists by checking with the file system.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Then call the `callback` argument with either true or false:`import { exists } from 'node:fs'; exists('/etc/passwd', (e) => { console.log(e ?
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] 'it exists' : 'no passwd!'); });`**The parameters for this callback are not consistent with other Node.js callbacks.** Normally, the first parameter to a Node.js callback is an `err` parameter, optionally followed by other parameters.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `fs.exists()` callback has only one boolean parameter.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] This is one reason `fs.access()` is recommended instead of `fs.exists()`.If `path` is a symbolic link, it is followed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Thus, if `path` exists but points to a non-existent element, the callback will receive the value `false`.Using `fs.exists()` to check for the existence of a file before calling `fs.open()`, `fs.readFile()`, or `fs.writeFile()` is not recommended.
