[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `lstat()` is identical to `stat()`, except that if `path` is a symbolic link, then the link itself is stat-ed, not the file that it refers to.See the POSIX `lstat(2)` documentation for more details.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Asynchronously creates a directory.The callback is given a possible exception and, if `recursive` is `true`, the first directory path created, `(err[, path])`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Calling `fs.mkdir()` when `path` is a directory that exists results in an error only when `recursive` is false.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Creates a unique temporary directory.Generates six random characters to be appended behind a required `prefix` to create a unique temporary directory.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] See the POSIX `open(2)` documentation for more details.`mode` sets the file mode (permission and sticky bits), but only if the file was created.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] On Windows, only the write permission can be manipulated; see `fs.chmod()`.The callback gets two arguments `(err, fd)`.Some characters (`< > : " / \ | ?
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Under NTFS, if the filename contains a colon, Node.js will open a file system stream, as described by this MSDN page.Functions based on `fs.open()` exhibit this behavior as well: `fs.writeFile()`, `fs.readFile()`, etc.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Returns a `<Blob>` whose data is backed by the given file.The file must not be modified after the `<Blob>` is created.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Any modifications will cause reading the `<Blob>` data to fail with a `DOMException` error.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] See the POSIX `opendir(3)` documentation for more details.Creates an `<fs.Dir>`, which contains all further functions for reading from and cleaning up the directory.The `encoding` option sets the encoding for the `path` while opening the directory and subsequent read operations.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `length` argument indicates the maximum number of bytes that Node.js will attempt to read from the kernel.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] However, the actual number of bytes read (`bytesRead`) can be lower than the specified `length` for various reasons.For example: If the file is shorter than the specified `length`, `bytesRead` will be set to the actual number of bytes read.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the file encounters EOF (End of File) before the buffer could be filled, Node.js will read all available bytes until EOF is encountered, and the `bytesRead` parameter in the callback will indicate the actual number of bytes read, which may be less than the specified `length`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the file is on a slow network `filesystem` or encounters any other issue during reading, `bytesRead` can be lower than the specified `length`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Therefore, when using `fs.read()`, it's important to check the `bytesRead` value to determine how many bytes were actually read from the file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Depending on your application logic, you may need to handle cases where `bytesRead` is lower than the specified `length`, such as by wrapping the read call in a loop if you require a minimum amount of bytes.This behavior is similar to the POSIX `preadv2` function.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Similar to the `fs.read()` function, this version takes an optional `options` object.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the `encoding` is set to `'buffer'`, the filenames returned will be passed as `<Buffer>` objects.If `options.withFileTypes` is set to `true`, the `files` array will contain `<fs.Dirent>` objects.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] On macOS, Linux, and Windows, an error will be returned.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If a file descriptor is specified as the `path`, it will not be closed automatically.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The reading will begin at the current position.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] For example, if the file already had `'Hello World'` and six bytes are read with the file descriptor, the call to `fs.readFile()` with the same file descriptor, would give `'World'`, rather than `'Hello World'`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `fs.readFile()` method asynchronously reads the contents of a file into memory one chunk at a time, allowing the event loop to turn between each chunk.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the file type is not a regular file (a pipe for instance) and Node.js is unable to determine an actual file size, each read operation will load on 64 KiB of data.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Read from a file specified by `fd` and write to an array of `ArrayBufferView`s using `readv()`.`position` is the offset from the beginning of the file from where data should be read.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If `typeof position !== 'number'`, the data will be read from the current position.The callback will be given three arguments: `err`, `bytesRead`, and `buffers`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `bytesRead` is how many bytes were read from the file.If this method is invoked as its `util.promisify()`ed version, it returns a promise for an `Object` with `bytesRead` and `buffers` properties.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Asynchronously computes the canonical pathname by resolving `.`, `..`, and symbolic links.A canonical pathname is not necessarily unique.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Hard links and bind mounts can expose a file system entity through many pathnames.This function behaves like `realpath(3)`, with some exceptions: No case conversion is performed on case-insensitive file systems.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The maximum number of symbolic links is platform-independent and generally (much) higher than what the native `realpath(3)` implementation supports.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `callback` gets two arguments `(err, resolvedPath)`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the `encoding` is set to `'buffer'`, the path returned will be passed as a `<Buffer>` object.If `path` resolves to a socket or a pipe, the function will return a system dependent name for that object.A path that does not exist results in an ENOENT error.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Asynchronously rename file at `oldPath` to the pathname provided as `newPath`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] In the case that `newPath` already exists, it will be overwritten.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If there is a directory at `newPath`, an error will be raised instead.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Asynchronously removes files and directories (modeled on the standard POSIX `rm` utility).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The callback gets two arguments `(err, stats)` where `stats` is an `<fs.Stats>` object.In case of an error, the `err.code` will be one of Common System Errors.`fs.stat()` follows symbolic links.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Use `fs.lstat()` to look at the links themselves.Using `fs.stat()` to check for the existence of a file before calling `fs.open()`, `fs.readFile()`, or `fs.writeFile()` is not recommended.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Returns information about the mounted file system which contains `path`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The callback gets two arguments `(err, stats)` where `stats` is an `<fs.StatFs>` object.In case of an error, the `err.code` will be one of Common System Errors.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Creates the link called `path` pointing to `target`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] No arguments other than a possible exception are given to the completion callback.See the POSIX `symlink(2)` documentation for more details.The `type` argument is only available on Windows and ignored on other platforms.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] A file descriptor can also be passed as the first argument.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Asynchronously removes a file or symbolic link.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] To remove a directory, use `fs.rmdir()`.See the POSIX `unlink(2)` documentation for more details.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Stop watching for changes on `filename`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If `listener` is specified, only that particular listener is removed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Otherwise, *all* listeners are removed, effectively stopping watching of `filename`.Calling `fs.unwatchFile()` with a filename that is not being watched is a no-op, not an error.Using `fs.watch()` is more efficient than `fs.watchFile()` and `fs.unwatchFile()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `fs.watch()` should be used instead of `fs.watchFile()` and `fs.unwatchFile()` when possible.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Change the file system timestamps of the object referenced by `path`.The `atime` and `mtime` arguments follow these rules: Values can be either numbers representing Unix epoch time in seconds, `Date`s, or a numeric string like `'123456789.0'`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Watch for changes on `filename`, where `filename` is either a file or a directory.The second argument is optional.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If `options` is provided as a string, it specifies the `encoding`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Otherwise `options` should be passed as an object.The listener callback gets two arguments `(eventType, filename)`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `fs.watch` API is not 100% consistent across platforms, and is unavailable in some situations.On Windows, no events will be emitted if the watched directory is moved or renamed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] An `EPERM` error is reported when the watched directory is deleted.The `fs.watch` API does not provide any protection with respect to malicious actions on the file system.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] For example, on Windows it is implemented by monitoring changes in a directory versus specific files.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] This allows substitution of a file and fs reporting changes on the new file with the same filename.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] This feature depends on the underlying operating system providing a way to be notified of file system changes.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] On Linux systems, this uses `inotify(7)`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] On macOS, this uses `kqueue(2)` for files and `FSEvents` for directories.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] On SunOS systems (including Solaris and SmartOS), this uses `event ports`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] On Windows systems, this feature depends on `ReadDirectoryChangesW`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] On AIX systems, this feature depends on `AHAFS`, which must be enabled.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] On IBM i systems, this feature is not supported.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the underlying functionality is not available for some reason, then `fs.watch()` will not be able to function and may throw an exception.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] On Linux and macOS systems, `fs.watch()` resolves the path to an inode and watches the inode.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the watched path is deleted and recreated, it is assigned a new inode.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The watch will emit an event for the delete but will continue watching the *original* inode.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Events for the new inode will not be emitted.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] This is expected behavior.AIX files retain the same inode for the lifetime of a file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Saving and closing a watched file on AIX will result in two notifications (one for adding new content, and one for truncation).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Providing `filename` argument in the callback is only supported on Linux, macOS, Windows, and AIX.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Even on supported platforms, `filename` is not always guaranteed to be provided.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The callback `listener` will be called each time the file is accessed.The `options` argument may be omitted.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `options` object may contain a boolean named `persistent` that indicates whether the process should continue to run as long as files are being watched.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the file is created later on, the listener will be called again, with the latest stat objects.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] This is a change in functionality since v0.10.Using `fs.watch()` is more efficient than `fs.watchFile` and `fs.unwatchFile`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Write `buffer` to the file specified by `fd`.`offset` determines the part of the buffer to be written, and `length` is an integer specifying the number of bytes to write.`position` refers to the offset from the beginning of the file where this data should be written.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If `typeof position !== 'number'`, the data will be written at the current position.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] For this scenario, `fs.createWriteStream()` is recommended.On Linux, positional writes don't work when the file is opened in append mode.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Write `buffer` to the file specified by `fd`.Similar to the above `fs.write` function, this version takes an optional `options` object.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Write `string` to the file specified by `fd`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If `string` is not a string, an exception is thrown.`position` refers to the offset from the beginning of the file where this data should be written.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If `typeof position !== 'number'` the data will be written at the current position.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] See `pwrite(2)`.`encoding` is the expected string encoding.The callback will receive the arguments `(err, written, string)` where `written` specifies how many *bytes* the passed string required to be written.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Bytes written is not necessarily the same as string characters written.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] See `Buffer.byteLength`.It is unsafe to use `fs.write()` multiple times on the same file without waiting for the callback.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The kernel ignores the position argument and always appends the data to the end of the file.On Windows, if the file descriptor is connected to the console (e.g.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `fd == 1` or `stdout`) a string containing non-ASCII characters will not be rendered properly by default, regardless of the encoding used.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] It is possible to configure the console to render UTF-8 properly by changing the active codepage with the `chcp 65001` command.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] When `file` is a filename, asynchronously writes data to the file, replacing the file if it already exists.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `data` can be a string or a buffer.When `file` is a file descriptor, the behavior is similar to calling `fs.write()` directly (which is recommended).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] See the notes below on using a file descriptor.The `encoding` option is ignored if `data` is a buffer.The `mode` option only affects the newly created file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] For this scenario, `fs.createWriteStream()` is recommended.Similarly to `fs.readFile` - `fs.writeFile` is a convenience method that performs multiple `write` calls internally to write the buffer passed to it.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] For performance sensitive code consider using `fs.createWriteStream()`.It is possible to use an `<AbortSignal>` to cancel an `fs.writeFile()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] In the file descriptor case, the file is not replaced!
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If a file name had been used instead of a descriptor, the file would be guaranteed to contain only `', World'`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Write an array of `ArrayBufferView`s to the file specified by `fd` using `writev()`.`position` is the offset from the beginning of the file where this data should be written.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If `typeof position !== 'number'`, the data will be written at the current position.The callback will be given three arguments: `err`, `bytesWritten`, and `buffers`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `bytesWritten` is how many bytes were written from `buffers`.If this method is `util.promisify()`ed, it returns a promise for an `Object` with `bytesWritten` and `buffers` properties.It is unsafe to use `fs.writev()` multiple times on the same file without waiting for the callback.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] For this scenario, use `fs.createWriteStream()`.On Linux, positional writes don't work when the file is opened in append mode.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The synchronous APIs perform all operations synchronously, blocking the event loop until the operation completes or fails.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Synchronously tests a user's permissions for the file or directory specified by `path`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Check File access constants for possible values of `mode`.If any of the accessibility checks fail, an `Error` will be thrown.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Synchronously append data to a file, creating the file if it does not yet exist.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.chmod()`.See the POSIX `chmod(2)` documentation for more detail.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Synchronously changes owner and group of a file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] This is the synchronous version of `fs.chown()`.See the POSIX `chown(2)` documentation for more detail.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Returns `undefined`.Calling `fs.closeSync()` on any file descriptor (`fd`) that is currently in use through any other `fs` operation may lead to undefined behavior.See the POSIX `close(2)` documentation for more detail.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Synchronously copies the entire directory structure from `src` to `dest`, including subdirectories and files.When copying a directory to another directory, globs are not supported and behavior is similar to `cp dir1/ dir2/`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Returns `true` if the path exists, `false` otherwise.For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.exists()`.`fs.exists()` is deprecated, but `fs.existsSync()` is not.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `callback` parameter to `fs.exists()` accepts parameters that are inconsistent with other Node.js callbacks.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Returns `undefined`.See the POSIX `fchmod(2)` documentation for more detail.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Returns `undefined`.See the POSIX `fchown(2)` documentation for more detail.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Retrieves the `<fs.Stats>` for the file descriptor.See the POSIX `fstat(2)` documentation for more detail.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns `undefined`.For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.ftruncate()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns `undefined`.This method is only implemented on macOS.See the POSIX `lchmod(2)` documentation for more detail.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns `undefined`.See the POSIX `lchown(2)` documentation for more details.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Change the file system timestamps of the symbolic link referenced by `path`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns `undefined`, or throws an exception when parameters are incorrect or the operation fails.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] This is the synchronous version of `fs.lutimes()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Retrieves the `<fs.Stats>` for the symbolic link referred to by `path`.See the POSIX `lstat(2)` documentation for more details.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns `undefined`, or if `recursive` is `true`, the first directory path created.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] This is the synchronous version of `fs.mkdir()`.See the POSIX `mkdir(2)` documentation for more details.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns the created directory path.For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.mkdtemp()`.The optional `options` argument can be a string specifying an encoding, or an object with an `encoding` property specifying the character encoding to use.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns a disposable object whose `path` property holds the created directory path.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] When the object is disposed, the directory and its contents will be removed if it still exists.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] See `opendir(3)`.Creates an `<fs.Dir>`, which contains all further functions for reading from and cleaning up the directory.The `encoding` option sets the encoding for the `path` while opening the directory and subsequent read operations.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns an integer representing the file descriptor.For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.open()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Reads the contents of the directory.See the POSIX `readdir(3)` documentation for more details.The optional `options` argument can be a string specifying an encoding, or an object with an `encoding` property specifying the character encoding to use for the filenames returned.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] If the `encoding` is set to `'buffer'`, the filenames returned will be passed as `<Buffer>` objects.If `options.withFileTypes` is set to `true`, the result will contain `<fs.Dirent>` objects.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns the contents of the `path`.For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.readFile()`.If the `encoding` option is specified then this function returns a string.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Otherwise it returns a buffer.If `buffer` is provided and no encoding is specified, the returned `<Buffer>` is a view over the supplied buffer containing only the bytes read.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns the symbolic link's string value.See the POSIX `readlink(2)` documentation for more details.The optional `options` argument can be a string specifying an encoding, or an object with an `encoding` property specifying the character encoding to use for the link path returned.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns the number of `bytesRead`.For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.read()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns the number of `bytesRead`.Similar to the above `fs.readSync` function, this version takes an optional `options` object.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] If no `options` object is specified, it will default with the above values.For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.read()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.readv()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns the resolved pathname.For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.realpath()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Synchronous `realpath(3)`.Only paths that can be converted to UTF8 strings are supported.The optional `options` argument can be a string specifying an encoding, or an object with an `encoding` property specifying the character encoding to use for the path returned.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Renames the file from `oldPath` to `newPath`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns `undefined`.See the POSIX `rename(2)` documentation for more details.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns `undefined`.Using `fs.rmdirSync()` on a file (not a directory) results in an `ENOENT` error on Windows and an `ENOTDIR` error on POSIX.To get a behavior similar to the `rm -rf` Unix command, use `fs.rmSync()` with options `{ recursive: true, force: true }`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Synchronously removes files and directories (modeled on the standard POSIX `rm` utility).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Retrieves the `<fs.Stats>` for the path.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns information about the mounted file system which contains `path`.In case of an error, the `err.code` will be one of Common System Errors.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.symlink()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] In this case, `fs.ftruncateSync()` is called.Passing a file descriptor is deprecated and may result in an error being thrown in the future.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.utimes()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The `mode` option only affects the newly created file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] See `fs.open()` for more details.For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.writeFile()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.write(fd, buffer...)`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.write(fd, string...)`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.writev()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The common objects are shared by all of the file system API variants (promise, callback, and synchronous).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Asynchronously close the directory's underlying resource handle.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Subsequent reads will result in errors.A promise is returned that will be fulfilled after the resource has been closed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Subsequent reads will result in errors.The `callback` will be called after the resource handle has been closed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Synchronously close the directory's underlying resource handle.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The read-only path of this directory as was provided to `fs.opendir()`, `fs.opendirSync()`, or `fsPromises.opendir()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Entries added or removed while iterating over the directory might not be included in the iteration results.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Synchronously read the next directory entry as an `<fs.Dirent>`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] See the POSIX `readdir(3)` documentation for more detail.If there are no more directory entries to read, `null` will be returned.Directory entries returned by this function are in no particular order as provided by the operating system's underlying directory mechanisms.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Asynchronously iterates over the directory until all entries have been read.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Refer to the POSIX `readdir(3)` documentation for more detail.Entries returned by the async iterator are always an `<fs.Dirent>`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The `null` case from `dir.read()` is handled internally.See `<fs.Dir>` for an example.Directory entries returned by this iterator are in no particular order as provided by the operating system's underlying directory mechanisms.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Calls `dir.close()` if the directory handle is open, and returns a promise that fulfills when disposal is complete.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Calls `dir.closeSync()` if the directory handle is open, and returns `undefined`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] A representation of a directory entry, which can be a file or a subdirectory within the directory, as returned by reading from an `<fs.Dir>`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The directory entry is a combination of the file name and file type pairs.Additionally, when `fs.readdir()` or `fs.readdirSync()` is called with the `withFileTypes` option set to `true`, the resulting array is filled with `<fs.Dirent>` objects, rather than strings or `<Buffer>`s.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Dirent>` object describes a block device.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Dirent>` object describes a character device.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Dirent>` object describes a file system directory.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Dirent>` object describes a first-in-first-out (FIFO) pipe.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Dirent>` object describes a regular file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Dirent>` object describes a socket.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Dirent>` object describes a symbolic link.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The file name that this `<fs.Dirent>` object refers to.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The type of this value is determined by the `options.encoding` passed to `fs.readdir()` or `fs.readdirSync()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The path to the parent directory of the file this `<fs.Dirent>` object refers to.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] A successful call to `fs.watch()` method will return a new `<fs.FSWatcher>` object.All `<fs.FSWatcher>` objects emit a `'change'` event whenever a specific watched file is modified.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Emitted when something changes in a watched directory or file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] See more details in `fs.watch()`.The `filename` argument may not be provided depending on operating system support.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Emitted when the watcher stops watching for changes.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The closed `<fs.FSWatcher>` object is no longer usable in the event handler.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Emitted when an error occurs while watching the file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The errored `<fs.FSWatcher>` object is no longer usable in the event handler.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Stop watching for changes on the given `<fs.FSWatcher>`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Once stopped, the `<fs.FSWatcher>` object is no longer usable.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] When called, requests that the Node.js event loop *not* exit so long as the `<fs.FSWatcher>` is active.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Calling `watcher.ref()` multiple times will have no effect.By default, all `<fs.FSWatcher>` objects are "ref'ed", making it normally unnecessary to call `watcher.ref()` unless `watcher.unref()` had been called previously.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] When called, the active `<fs.FSWatcher>` object will not require the Node.js event loop to remain active.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] If there is no other activity keeping the event loop running, the process may exit before the `<fs.FSWatcher>` object's callback is invoked.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Calling `watcher.unref()` multiple times will have no effect.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] A successful call to `fs.watchFile()` method will return a new `<fs.StatWatcher>` object.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] When called, requests that the Node.js event loop *not* exit so long as the `<fs.StatWatcher>` is active.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Calling `watcher.ref()` multiple times will have no effect.By default, all `<fs.StatWatcher>` objects are "ref'ed", making it normally unnecessary to call `watcher.ref()` unless `watcher.unref()` had been called previously.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] When called, the active `<fs.StatWatcher>` object will not require the Node.js event loop to remain active.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] If there is no other activity keeping the event loop running, the process may exit before the `<fs.StatWatcher>` object's callback is invoked.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Instances of `<fs.ReadStream>` cannot be constructed directly.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] They are created and returned using the `fs.createReadStream()` function.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Emitted when the `<fs.ReadStream>`'s underlying file descriptor has been closed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Emitted when the `<fs.ReadStream>`'s file descriptor has been opened.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Emitted when the `<fs.ReadStream>` is ready to be used.Fires immediately after `'open'`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The number of bytes that have been read so far.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The path to the file the stream is reading from as specified in the first argument to `fs.createReadStream()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] If `path` is passed as a string, then `readStream.path` will be a string.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] If `path` is passed as a `<Buffer>`, then `readStream.path` will be a `<Buffer>`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] If `fd` is specified, then `readStream.path` will be `undefined`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] This property is `true` if the underlying file has not been opened yet, i.e. before the `'ready'` event is emitted.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] A `<fs.Stats>` object provides information about a file.Objects returned from `fs.stat()`, `fs.lstat()`, `fs.fstat()`, and their synchronous counterparts are of this type.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] If `bigint` in the `options` passed to those methods is true, the numeric values will be `bigint` instead of `number`, and the object will contain additional nanosecond-precision properties suffixed with `Ns`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Stats>` object describes a block device.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Stats>` object describes a character device.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Stats>` object describes a file system directory.If the `<fs.Stats>` object was obtained from calling `fs.lstat()` on a symbolic link which resolves to a directory, this method will return `false`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] This is because `fs.lstat()` returns information about a symbolic link itself and not the path it resolves to.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Stats>` object describes a first-in-first-out (FIFO) pipe.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Stats>` object describes a regular file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Stats>` object describes a socket.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Stats>` object describes a symbolic link.This method is only valid when using `fs.lstat()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The numeric identifier of the device containing the file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The file system specific "Inode" number for the file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] A bit-field describing the file type and mode.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The number of hard-links that exist for the file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The numeric user identifier of the user that owns the file (POSIX).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The numeric group identifier of the group that owns the file (POSIX).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] A numeric device identifier if the file represents a device.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The size of the file in bytes.If the underlying file system does not support getting the size of the file, this will be `0`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The file system block size for i/o operations.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The number of blocks allocated for this file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The timestamp indicating the last time this file was accessed expressed in milliseconds since the POSIX Epoch.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The timestamp indicating the last time this file was modified expressed in milliseconds since the POSIX Epoch.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The timestamp indicating the last time the file status was changed expressed in milliseconds since the POSIX Epoch.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The timestamp indicating the creation time of this file expressed in milliseconds since the POSIX Epoch.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Only present when `bigint: true` is passed into the method that generates the object.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The timestamp indicating the last time this file was accessed expressed in nanoseconds since the POSIX Epoch.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The timestamp indicating the last time this file was modified expressed in nanoseconds since the POSIX Epoch.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The timestamp indicating the last time the file status was changed expressed in nanoseconds since the POSIX Epoch.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The timestamp indicating the creation time of this file expressed in nanoseconds since the POSIX Epoch.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The timestamp indicating the last time this file was accessed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The timestamp indicating the last time this file was modified.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The timestamp indicating the last time the file status was changed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The timestamp indicating the creation time of this file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The `atimeMs`, `mtimeMs`, `ctimeMs`, `birthtimeMs` properties are numeric values that hold the corresponding times in milliseconds.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] When `bigint: true` is passed into the method that generates the object, the properties will be bigints, otherwise they will be numbers.The `atimeNs`, `mtimeNs`, `ctimeNs`, `birthtimeNs` properties are bigints that hold the corresponding times in nanoseconds.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] They are only present when `bigint: true` is passed into the method that generates the object.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Their precision is platform specific.`atime`, `mtime`, `ctime`, and `birthtime` are `Date` object alternate representations of the various times.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The `Date` and number values are not connected.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Assigning a new number value, or mutating the `Date` value, will not be reflected in the corresponding alternate representation.The times in the stat object have the following semantics: `atime` "Access Time": Time when file data last accessed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Changed by the `mknod(2)`, `utimes(2)`, and `read(2)` system calls.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `mtime` "Modified Time": Time when file data last modified.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Changed by the `mknod(2)`, `utimes(2)`, and `write(2)` system calls.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `ctime` "Change Time": Time when file status was last changed (inode data modification).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `birthtime` "Birth Time": Time of file creation.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] On file systems where birthtime is not available, this field may instead hold either the `ctime` or `1970-01-01T00:00Z` (ie, Unix epoch timestamp `0`).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] This value may be greater than `atime` or `mtime` in this case.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] On Darwin and other FreeBSD variants, also set if the `atime` is explicitly set to an earlier value than the current `birthtime` using the `utimes(2)` system call.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Prior to Node.js 0.12, the `ctime` held the `birthtime` on Windows systems.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] As of 0.12, `ctime` is not "creation time", and on Unix systems, it never was.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Provides information about a mounted file system.Objects returned from `fs.statfs()` and its synchronous counterpart are of this type.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Free blocks available to unprivileged users.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] A platform-specific numeric identifier for the type of file system.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] This value corresponds to the `f_type` field returned by `statfs(2)` on POSIX systems (for example, `0xEF53` for ext4 on Linux).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Its meaning is OS-dependent and is not guaranteed to be consistent across platforms.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] An optimized UTF-8 stream writer that allows for flushing all the internal buffering on demand.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] It handles `EAGAIN` errors correctly, allowing for customization, for example, by dropping content if the disk is busy.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The `'close'` event is emitted when the stream is fully closed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The `'drain'` event is emitted when the internal buffer has drained sufficiently to allow continued writing.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The `'drop'` event is emitted when the maximal length is reached and that data will not be written.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The data that was dropped is passed as the first argument to the event handler.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The `'error'` event is emitted when an error occurs.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The `'finish'` event is emitted when the stream has been ended and all data has been flushed to the underlying file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The `'ready'` event is emitted when the stream is ready to accept writes.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The `'write'` event is emitted when a write operation has completed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The number of bytes written is passed as the first argument to the event handler.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Close the stream immediately, without flushing the internal buffer.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Close the stream gracefully, flushing the internal buffer before closing.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Writes the current buffer to the file if a write was not in progress.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Do nothing if `minLength` is zero or if it is already writing.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Flushes the buffered data synchronously.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Reopen the file in place, useful for log rotation.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] When the `options.contentMode` is set to `'utf8'` when the stream is created, the `data` argument must be a string.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] If the `contentMode` is set to `'buffer'`, the `data` argument must be a `<Buffer>`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Instances of `<fs.WriteStream>` cannot be constructed directly.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] They are created and returned using the `fs.createWriteStream()` function.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Emitted when the `<fs.WriteStream>`'s underlying file descriptor has been closed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Emitted when the `<fs.WriteStream>`'s file is opened.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Emitted when the `<fs.WriteStream>` is ready to be used.Fires immediately after `'open'`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Does not include data that is still queued for writing.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Optionally accepts a callback that will be executed once the `writeStream` is closed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The path to the file the stream is writing to as specified in the first argument to `fs.createWriteStream()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] If `path` is passed as a string, then `writeStream.path` will be a string.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] If `path` is passed as a `<Buffer>`, then `writeStream.path` will be a `<Buffer>`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The following constants are exported by `fs.constants` and `fsPromises.constants`.Not every constant will be available on every operating system; this is especially important for Windows, where many of the POSIX specific definitions are not available.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The following constants are meant for use as the `mode` parameter passed to `fsPromises.access()`, `fs.access()`, and `fs.accessSync()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Constant Description `F_OK` Flag indicating that the file is visible to the calling process.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] This is useful for determining if a file exists, but says nothing about `rwx` permissions.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `R_OK` Flag indicating that the file can be read by the calling process.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `W_OK` Flag indicating that the file can be written by the calling process.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `X_OK` Flag indicating that the file can be executed by the calling process.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] This has no effect on Windows (will behave like `fs.constants.F_OK`).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The definitions are also available on Windows.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The following constants are meant for use with `fs.copyFile()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Constant Description `COPYFILE_EXCL` If present, the copy operation will fail with an error if the destination path already exists.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `COPYFILE_FICLONE` If present, the copy operation will attempt to create a copy-on-write reflink.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] If the underlying platform does not support copy-on-write, then a fallback copy mechanism is used.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `COPYFILE_FICLONE_FORCE` If present, the copy operation will attempt to create a copy-on-write reflink.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] If the underlying platform does not support copy-on-write, then the operation will fail with an error.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The following constants are meant for use with `fs.open()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Constant Description `O_RDONLY` Flag indicating to open a file for read-only access.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_WRONLY` Flag indicating to open a file for write-only access.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_RDWR` Flag indicating to open a file for read-write access.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_CREAT` Flag indicating to create the file if it does not already exist.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_EXCL` Flag indicating that opening a file should fail if the `O_CREAT` flag is set and the file already exists.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_NOCTTY` Flag indicating that if path identifies a terminal device, opening the path shall not cause that terminal to become the controlling terminal for the process (if the process does not already have one).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_TRUNC` Flag indicating that if the file exists and is a regular file, and the file is opened successfully for write access, its length shall be truncated to zero.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_APPEND` Flag indicating that data will be appended to the end of the file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_DIRECTORY` Flag indicating that the open should fail if the path is not a directory.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_NOATIME` Flag indicating reading accesses to the file system will no longer result in an update to the `atime` information associated with the file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] This flag is available on Linux operating systems only.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_NOFOLLOW` Flag indicating that the open should fail if the path is a symbolic link.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_SYNC` Flag indicating that the file is opened for synchronized I/O with write operations waiting for file integrity.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_DSYNC` Flag indicating that the file is opened for synchronized I/O with write operations waiting for data integrity.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_SYMLINK` Flag indicating to open the symbolic link itself rather than the resource it is pointing to.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_DIRECT` When set, an attempt will be made to minimize caching effects of file I/O.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_NONBLOCK` Flag indicating to open the file in nonblocking mode when possible.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `UV_FS_O_FILEMAP` When set, a memory file mapping is used to access the file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] This flag is available on Windows operating systems only.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] On other operating systems, this flag is ignored.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] On Windows, only `O_APPEND`, `O_CREAT`, `O_EXCL`, `O_RDONLY`, `O_RDWR`, `O_TRUNC`, `O_WRONLY`, and `UV_FS_O_FILEMAP` are available.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The following constants are meant for use with the `<fs.Stats>` object's `mode` property for determining a file's type.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Constant Description `S_IFMT` Bit mask used to extract the file type code.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IFREG` File type constant for a regular file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IFDIR` File type constant for a directory.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IFCHR` File type constant for a character-oriented device file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IFBLK` File type constant for a block-oriented device file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IFIFO` File type constant for a FIFO/pipe.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IFLNK` File type constant for a symbolic link.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IFSOCK` File type constant for a socket.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] On Windows, only `S_IFCHR`, `S_IFDIR`, `S_IFLNK`, `S_IFMT`, and `S_IFREG`, are available.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The following constants are meant for use with the `<fs.Stats>` object's `mode` property for determining the access permissions for a file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Constant Description `S_IRWXU` File mode indicating readable, writable, and executable by owner.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IRUSR` File mode indicating readable by owner.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IWUSR` File mode indicating writable by owner.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IXUSR` File mode indicating executable by owner.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IRWXG` File mode indicating readable, writable, and executable by group.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IRGRP` File mode indicating readable by group.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IWGRP` File mode indicating writable by group.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IXGRP` File mode indicating executable by group.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IRWXO` File mode indicating readable, writable, and executable by others.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IROTH` File mode indicating readable by others.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IWOTH` File mode indicating writable by others.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IXOTH` File mode indicating executable by others.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] On Windows, only `S_IRUSR` and `S_IWUSR` are available.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This module, containing both a client and server, can be imported via `require('node:http')` (CommonJS) or `import * as http from 'node:http'` (ES module).The HTTP interfaces in Node.js are designed to support many features of the protocol which have been traditionally difficult to use.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] In particular, large, possibly chunk-encoded, messages.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Values are not modified.In order to support the full spectrum of possible HTTP applications, the Node.js HTTP API is very low-level.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] It deals with stream handling and message parsing only.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] An `Agent` is responsible for managing connection persistence and reuse for HTTP clients.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] It maintains a queue of pending requests for a given host and port, reusing a single socket connection for each until the queue is empty, at which time the socket is either destroyed or put into a pool where it is kept to be used again for requests to the same host and port.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Servers may also refuse to allow multiple requests over the same connection, in which case the connection will have to be remade for every request and cannot be pooled.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The `Agent` will still make the requests to that server, but each one will occur over a new connection.When a connection is closed by the client or the server, it is removed from the pool.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Any unused sockets in the pool will be unrefed so as not to keep the Node.js process running when there are no outstanding requests.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] (see `socket.unref()`).It is good practice, to `destroy()` an `Agent` instance when it is no longer in use, because unused sockets consume OS resources.Sockets are removed from an agent when the socket emits either a `'close'` event or an `'agentRemove'` event.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] When intending to keep one HTTP request open for a long time without keeping it in the agent, something like the following may be done:`http.get(options, (res) => { // Do stuff }).on('socket', (socket) => { socket.emit('agentRemove'); });`An agent may also be used for an individual request.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Produces a socket/stream to be used for HTTP requests.By default, this function behaves identically to `net.createConnection()`, synchronously returning the created socket.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The optional `callback` parameter in the signature is **not** used by this default implementation.However, custom agents may override this method to provide greater flexibility, for example, to create sockets asynchronously.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] When overriding `createConnection`: **Synchronous socket creation**: The overriding method can return the socket/stream directly.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] **Asynchronous socket creation**: The overriding method can accept the `callback` and pass the created socket/stream to it (e.g., `callback(null, newSocket)`).
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If an error occurs during socket creation, it should be passed as the first argument to the `callback` (e.g., `callback(err)`).
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The agent will call the provided `createConnection` function with `options` and this internal `callback`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The `callback` provided by the agent has a signature of `(err, stream)`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Called when `socket` is detached from a request and could be persisted by the `Agent`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Default behavior is to:`socket.setKeepAlive(true, this.keepAliveMsecs); socket.unref(); return true;`This method can be overridden by a particular `Agent` subclass.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If this method returns a falsy value, the socket will be destroyed instead of persisting it for use with the next request.The `socket` argument can be an instance of `<net.Socket>`, a subclass of `<stream.Duplex>`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Called when `socket` is attached to `request` after being persisted because of the keep-alive options.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Default behavior is to:`socket.ref();`This method can be overridden by a particular `Agent` subclass.The `socket` argument can be an instance of `<net.Socket>`, a subclass of `<stream.Duplex>`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Destroy any sockets that are currently in use by the agent.It is usually not necessary to do this.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] However, if using an agent with `keepAlive` enabled, then it is best to explicitly shut down the agent when it is no longer needed.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Otherwise, sockets might stay open for quite a long time before the server terminates them.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] An object which contains arrays of sockets currently awaiting use by the agent when `keepAlive` is enabled.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Do not modify.Sockets in the `freeSockets` list will be automatically destroyed and removed from the array on `'timeout'`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Get a unique name for a set of request options, to determine whether a connection can be reused.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] For an HTTP agent, this returns `host:port:localAddress` or `host:port:localAddress:family`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] For an HTTPS agent, the name includes the CA, cert, ciphers, and other HTTPS/TLS-specific options that determine socket reusability.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] For agents with `keepAlive` enabled, this sets the maximum number of sockets that will be left open in the free state.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Determines how many concurrent sockets the agent can have open per origin.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Origin is the returned value of `agent.getName()`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Determines how many concurrent sockets the agent can have open.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Unlike `maxSockets`, this parameter applies across all origins.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] An object which contains queues of requests that have not yet been assigned to sockets.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] An object which contains arrays of sockets currently in use by the agent.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This object is created internally and returned from `http.request()`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] It represents an *in-progress* request whose header has already been queued.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The header is still mutable using the `setHeader(name, value)`, `getHeader(name)`, `removeHeader(name)` API.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The actual header will be sent along with the first data chunk or when calling `request.end()`.To get the response, add a listener for `'response'` to the request object.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] `'response'` will be emitted from the request object when the response headers have been received.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] However, if a `'response'` event handler is added, then the data from the response object **must** be consumed, either by calling `response.read()` whenever there is a `'readable'` event, or by adding a `'data'` handler, or by calling the `.resume()` method.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Until the data is consumed, the `'end'` event will not fire.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Also, until the data is read it will consume memory that can eventually lead to a 'process out of memory' error.For backward compatibility, `res` will only emit `'error'` if there is an `'error'` listener registered.Set `Content-Length` header to limit the response body size.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If `response.strictContentLength` is set to `true`, mismatching the `Content-Length` header value will result in an `Error` being thrown, identified by `code:` `'ERR_HTTP_CONTENT_LENGTH_MISMATCH'`.`Content-Length` value should be in bytes, not characters.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Use `Buffer.byteLength()` to determine the length of the body in bytes.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Emitted when the request has been aborted by the client.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This event is only emitted on the first call to `abort()`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Indicates that the request is completed, or its underlying connection was terminated prematurely (before the response completion).
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Emitted each time a server responds to a request with a `CONNECT` method.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Emitted when the server sends a '100 Continue' HTTP response, usually because the request contained 'Expect: 100-continue'.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This is an instruction that the client should send the request body.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] More specifically, this event is emitted when the last segment of the request headers and body have been handed off to the operating system for transmission over the network.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] It does not imply that the server has received anything yet.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Emitted when the server sends a 1xx intermediate response (excluding 101 Upgrade).
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] To be notified of 101 Upgrade notices, listen for the `'upgrade'` event instead.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Emitted when a response is received to this request.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This event is guaranteed to be passed an instance of the `<net.Socket>` class, a subclass of `<stream.Duplex>`, unless the user specifies a socket type other than `<net.Socket>`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Emitted when the underlying socket times out from inactivity.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This only notifies that the socket has been idle.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The request must be destroyed manually.See also: `request.setTimeout()`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Emitted each time a server responds to a request with an upgrade.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Stability: 0 - Deprecated: Use `request.destroy()` instead.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Calling this will cause remaining data in the response to be dropped and the socket to be destroyed.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The `request.aborted` property will be `true` if the request has been aborted.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If any parts of the body are unsent, it will flush them to the stream.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If the request is chunked, this will send the terminating `'0\r\n\r\n'`.If `data` is specified, it is equivalent to calling `request.write(data, encoding)` followed by `request.end(callback)`.If `callback` is specified, it will be called when the request stream is finished.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Optionally emit an `'error'` event, and emit a `'close'` event.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Calling this will cause remaining data in the response to be dropped, and the socket to be destroyed if used, or returned to the corresponding Agent pool otherwise if possible.See `writable.destroy()` for further details.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Is `true` after `request.destroy()` has been called.See `writable.destroyed` for further details.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The `request.finished` property will be `true` if `request.end()` has been called.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] `request.end()` will automatically be called if the request was initiated via `http.get()`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Flushes the request headers.For efficiency reasons, Node.js normally buffers the request headers until `request.end()` is called or the first chunk of request data is written.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] It then tries to pack the request headers and data into a single TCP packet.That's usually desired (it saves a TCP round-trip), but not when the first data is not sent until possibly much later.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] `request.flushHeaders()` bypasses the optimization and kickstarts the request.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Returns an array containing the unique names of the current outgoing headers.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Returns a shallow copy of the current outgoing headers.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Since a shallow copy is used, array values may be mutated without additional calls to various header-related http module methods.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The keys of the returned object are the header names and the values are the respective header values.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] All header names are lowercase.The object returned by the `request.getHeaders()` method *does not* prototypically inherit from the JavaScript `Object`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Returns an array containing the unique names of the current outgoing raw headers.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Returns `true` if the header identified by `name` is currently set in the outgoing headers.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] When sending request through a keep-alive enabled agent, the underlying socket might be reused.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Sets a single header value for headers object.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If this header already exists in the to-be-sent headers, its value will be replaced.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Use an array of strings here to send multiple headers with the same name.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Non-string values will be stored without modification.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Therefore, `request.getHeader()` may return non-string values.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Once a socket is assigned to this request and is connected `socket.setNoDelay()` will be called.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Once a socket is assigned to this request and is connected `socket.setKeepAlive()` will be called.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Once a socket is assigned to this request and is connected `socket.setTimeout()` will be called.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Usually users will not want to access this property.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Is `true` after `request.end()` has been called.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This property does not indicate whether the data has been flushed, for this use `request.writableFinished` instead.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Is `true` if all data has been flushed to the underlying system, immediately before the `'finish'` event is emitted.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This method can be called multiple times.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If no `Content-Length` is set, data will automatically be encoded in HTTP Chunked transfer encoding, so that server knows when the data ends.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` header is added.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Calling `request.end()` is necessary to finish sending the request.The `encoding` argument is optional and only applies when `chunk` is a string.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Defaults to `'utf8'`.The `callback` argument is optional and will be called when this chunk of data is flushed, but only if the chunk is non-empty.Returns `true` if the entire data was flushed successfully to the kernel buffer.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Returns `false` if all or part of the data was queued in user memory.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] `'drain'` will be emitted when the buffer is free again.When `write` function is called with empty string or buffer, it does nothing and waits for more input.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Emitted each time a request with an HTTP `Expect: 100-continue` is received.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If this event is not listened for, the server will automatically respond with a `100 Continue` as appropriate.Handling this event involves calling `response.writeContinue()` if the client should continue to send the request body, or generating an appropriate HTTP response (e.g.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] 400 Bad Request) if the client should not continue to send the request body.When this event is emitted and handled, the `'request'` event will not be emitted.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Emitted each time a request with an HTTP `Expect` header is received, where the value is not `100-continue`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If this event is not listened for, the server will automatically respond with a `417 Expectation Failed` as appropriate.When this event is emitted and handled, the `'request'` event will not be emitted.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If a client connection emits an `'error'` event, it will be forwarded here.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Listener of this event is responsible for closing/destroying the underlying socket.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] For example, one may wish to more gracefully close the socket with a custom HTTP response instead of abruptly severing the connection.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Care must be taken to ensure the response is a properly formatted HTTP response message.`err` is an instance of `Error` with two extra columns: `bytesParsed`: the bytes count of request packet that Node.js may have parsed correctly; `rawPacket`: the raw packet of current request.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] In some cases, the client has already received the response and/or the socket has already been destroyed, like in case of `ECONNRESET` errors.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Emitted each time a client requests an HTTP `CONNECT` method.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This event is emitted when a new TCP stream is established.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] `socket` is typically an object of type `net.Socket`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Usually users will not want to access this event.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] In particular, the socket will not emit `'readable'` events because of how the protocol parser attaches to the socket.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The `socket` can also be accessed at `request.socket`.This event can also be explicitly emitted by users to inject connections into the HTTP server.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] When the number of requests on a socket reaches the threshold of `server.maxRequestsPerSocket`, the server will drop new requests and emit `'dropRequest'` event instead, then send `503` to client.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] There may be multiple requests per connection (in the case of HTTP Keep-Alive connections).
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Emitted each time a client's HTTP upgrade request is accepted.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] To ensure that reading from the stream isn't blocked by waiting for the request body to be read, any reads on the stream will start the request body flowing automatically.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If required, you can access the raw connection underlying the request via `request.socket`, which is guaranteed to be an instance of `<net.Socket>` unless the user specified another socket type.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Stops the server from accepting new connections and closes all connections connected to this server which are not sending a request or waiting for a response.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Closes all established HTTP(S) connections connected to this server, including active connections connected to this server which are sending a request or waiting for a response.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This does *not* destroy sockets upgraded to a different protocol, such as WebSocket or HTTP/2.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This is a forceful way of closing all connections and should be used with caution.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Whenever using this in conjunction with `server.close`, calling this *after* `server.close` is recommended as to avoid race conditions where new connections are created between a call to this and a call to `server.close`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Closes all connections connected to this server which are not sending a request or waiting for a response.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Starting with Node.js 19.0.0, there's no need for calling this method in conjunction with `server.close` to reap `keep-alive` connections.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Using it won't cause any harm though, and it can be useful to ensure backwards compatibility for libraries and applications that need to support versions older than 19.0.0.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Limit the amount of time the parser will wait to receive the complete HTTP headers.If the timeout expires, the server responds with status 408 without forwarding the request to the request listener and then closes the connection.It must be set to a non-zero value (e.g.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] 120 seconds) to protect against potential Denial-of-Service attacks in case the server is deployed without a reverse proxy in front.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Starts the HTTP server listening for connections.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This method is identical to `server.listen()` from `net.Server`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Sets the timeout value in milliseconds for receiving the entire request from the client.If the timeout expires, the server responds with status 408 without forwarding the request to the request listener and then closes the connection.It must be set to a non-zero value (e.g.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] However, if a callback is assigned to the Server's `'timeout'` event, timeouts must be handled explicitly.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] A value of `0` makes the HTTP server behave similarly to Node.js versions prior to 8.0.0, which did not have a keep-alive timeout.The socket timeout logic is set up on connection, so changing this value only affects new connections to the server, not any existing connections.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Calls `server.close()` and returns a promise that fulfills when the server has closed.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This object is created internally by an HTTP server, not by the user.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] It is passed as the second parameter to the `'request'` event.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Indicates that the response is completed, or its underlying connection was terminated prematurely (before the response completion).
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Emitted when the response has been sent.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] More specifically, this event is emitted when the last segment of the response headers and body have been handed off to the operating system for transmission over the network.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] It does not imply that the client has received anything yet.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This method signals to the server that all of the response headers and body have been sent; that server should consider this message complete.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The method, `response.end()`, MUST be called on each response.If `data` is specified, it is similar in effect to calling `response.write(data, encoding)` followed by `response.end(callback)`.If `callback` is specified, it will be called when the response stream is finished.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The `response.finished` property will be `true` if `response.end()` has been called.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Reads out a header that's already been queued but not sent to the client.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] All header names are lowercase.The object returned by the `response.getHeaders()` method *does not* prototypically inherit from the JavaScript `Object`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] True if headers were sent, false otherwise.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] A reference to the original HTTP `request` object.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] When true, the Date header will be automatically generated and sent in the response if it is not already present in the headers.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] Defaults to true.This should only be disabled for testing; the Date header is required in most HTTP responses (see RFC 9110 Section 6.6.1 for details).
