[src:javascript/api-http-p03] Flushes the message headers.For efficiency reason, Node.js normally buffers the message headers until `outgoingMessage.end()` is called or the first chunk of message data is written.
[src:javascript/api-http-p03] It then tries to pack the headers and data into a single TCP packet.It is usually desired (it saves a TCP round-trip), but not when the first data is not sent until possibly much later.
[src:javascript/api-http-p03] `outgoingMessage.flushHeaders()` bypasses the optimization and kickstarts the message.
