[src:javascript/api-http-p03] Dynamically resets the global configurations to enable built-in proxy support for `fetch()` and `http.request()`/`https.request()` at runtime, as an alternative to using the `--use-env-proxy` flag or `NODE_USE_ENV_PROXY` environment variable.
[src:javascript/api-http-p03] It can also be used to override settings configured from the environment variables.As this function resets the global configurations, any previously configured `http.globalAgent`, `https.globalAgent` or undici global dispatcher would be overridden after this function is invoked.
[src:javascript/api-http-p03] It's recommended to invoke it before any requests are made and avoid invoking it in the middle of any requests.See Built-in Proxy Support for details on proxy URL formats and `NO_PROXY` syntax.
[src:javascript/api-http-p03] A browser-compatible implementation of `<WebSocket>`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p03] The value can be `process.env` if they just want to inherit the configuration from the environment variables, or an object with specific setting overriding the environment.The following properties of the `proxyEnv` are checked to configure proxy support.
[src:javascript/api-http-p03] `HTTP_PROXY` or `http_proxy`: Proxy server URL for HTTP requests.
[src:javascript/api-http-p03] If both are set, `http_proxy` takes precedence.
[src:javascript/api-http-p03] `HTTPS_PROXY` or `https_proxy`: Proxy server URL for HTTPS requests.
[src:javascript/api-http-p03] If both are set, `https_proxy` takes precedence.
[src:javascript/api-http-p03] `NO_PROXY` or `no_proxy`: Comma-separated list of hosts to bypass the proxy.
[src:javascript/api-http-p03] If both are set, `no_proxy` takes precedence.
[src:javascript/api-http-p03] If the request is made to a Unix domain socket, the proxy settings will be ignored.
[src:javascript/api-path] The `node:path` module provides utilities for working with file and directory paths.
[src:javascript/api-path] The default operation of the `node:path` module varies based on the operating system on which a Node.js application is running.
[src:javascript/api-path] This behavior can be observed when using a drive path without a backslash.
[src:javascript/api-path] For example, `path.resolve('C:\\')` can potentially return a different result than `path.resolve('C:')`.
[src:javascript/api-path] For more information, see this MSDN page.
[src:javascript/api-path] The `path.basename()` method returns the last portion of a `path`, similar to the Unix `basename` command.
[src:javascript/api-path] The `path.dirname()` method returns the directory name of a `path`, similar to the Unix `dirname` command.
[src:javascript/api-path] Trailing directory separators are ignored, see `path.sep`.`path.dirname('/foo/bar/baz/asdf/quux'); // Returns: '/foo/bar/baz/asdf'`A `TypeError` is thrown if `path` is not a string.
[src:javascript/api-path] The `path.extname()` method returns the extension of the `path`, from the last occurrence of the `.` (period) character to end of string in the last portion of the `path`.
[src:javascript/api-path] The `path.format()` method returns a path string from an object.
[src:javascript/api-path] `root` is ignored. path.format({ root: '/ignored', dir: '/home/user/dir', base: 'file.txt', }); // Returns: '/home/user/dir/file.txt' // `root` will be used if `dir` is not specified. // If only `root` is provided or `dir` is equal to `root` then the // platform separator will not be included.
[src:javascript/api-path] The `path.matchesGlob()` method determines if `path` matches the `pattern`.For example:`path.matchesGlob('/foo/bar', '/foo/*'); // true path.matchesGlob('/foo/bar*', 'foo/bird'); // false`A `TypeError` is thrown if `path` or `pattern` are not strings.
[src:javascript/api-path] The `path.isAbsolute()` method determines if the literal `path` is absolute.
[src:javascript/api-path] The `path.join()` method joins all given `path` segments together using the platform-specific separator as a delimiter, then normalizes the resulting path.Zero-length `path` segments are ignored.
[src:javascript/api-path] If the joined path string is a zero-length string then `'.'` will be returned, representing the current working directory.`path.join('/foo', 'bar', 'baz/asdf', 'quux', '..'); // Returns: '/foo/bar/baz/asdf' path.join('foo', {}, 'bar'); // Throws 'TypeError: Path must be a string.
[src:javascript/api-path] Received {}'`A `TypeError` is thrown if any of the path segments is not a string.
[src:javascript/api-path] The `path.normalize()` method normalizes the given `path`, resolving `'..'` and `'.'` segments.When multiple, sequential path segment separation characters are found (e.g.
[src:javascript/api-path] `/` on POSIX and either `\` or `/` on Windows), they are replaced by a single instance of the platform-specific path segment separator (`/` on POSIX and `\` on Windows).
[src:javascript/api-path] Trailing separators are preserved.If the `path` is a zero-length string, `'.'` is returned, representing the current working directory.On POSIX, the types of normalization applied by this function do not strictly adhere to the POSIX specification.
[src:javascript/api-path] For example, this function will replace two leading forward slashes with a single slash as if it was a regular absolute path, whereas a few POSIX systems assign special meaning to paths beginning with exactly two forward slashes.
[src:javascript/api-path] The `path.parse()` method returns an object whose properties represent significant elements of the `path`.
[src:javascript/api-path] They are purely for formatting.)`A `TypeError` is thrown if `path` is not a string.
[src:javascript/api-path] The `path.posix` property provides access to POSIX specific implementations of the `path` methods.The API is accessible via `require('node:path').posix` or `require('node:path/posix')`.
[src:javascript/api-path] The `path.relative()` method returns the relative path from `from` to `to` based on the current working directory.
[src:javascript/api-path] The `path.resolve()` method resolves a sequence of paths or path segments into an absolute path.The given sequence of paths is processed from right to left, with each subsequent `path` prepended until an absolute path is constructed.
[src:javascript/api-path] On Windows systems only, returns an equivalent namespace-prefixed path for the given `path`.
[src:javascript/api-path] If `path` is not a string, `path` will be returned without modifications.This method is meaningful only on Windows systems.
[src:javascript/api-path] On POSIX systems, the method is non-operational and always returns `path` without modifications.
[src:javascript/api-path] The `path.win32` property provides access to Windows-specific implementations of the `path` methods.The API is accessible via `require('node:path').win32` or `require('node:path/win32')`.
[src:javascript/async-function] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:javascript/async-function] It’s been available across browsers since April 2017.
[src:javascript/async-function] The **`async function`** declaration creates a binding of a new async function to a given name.
[src:javascript/async-function] The `await` keyword is permitted within the function body, enabling asynchronous, promise-based behavior to be written in a cleaner style and avoiding the need to explicitly configure promise chains.
[src:javascript/async-function] You can also define async functions using the `async function` expression.
[src:javascript/async-function] The name of a formal parameter for the function.
[src:javascript/async-function] For the parameters' syntax, see the Functions reference.
[src:javascript/async-function] The statements comprising the body of the function.
[src:javascript/async-function] An `async function` declaration creates an `AsyncFunction` object.
[src:javascript/async-function] Each time when an async function is called, it returns a new `Promise` which will be resolved with the value returned by the async function, or rejected with an exception uncaught within the async function.
[src:javascript/async-function] Async functions can contain zero or more `await` expressions.
[src:javascript/async-function] Await expressions make promise-returning functions behave as though they're synchronous by suspending execution until the returned promise is fulfilled or rejected.
[src:javascript/async-function] The resolved value of the promise is treated as the return value of the await expression.
[src:javascript/async-function] Use of `async` and `await` enables the use of ordinary `try` / `catch` blocks around asynchronous code.
[src:javascript/async-function] `await` can be used on its own with JavaScript modules.
[src:javascript/async-function] Async functions always return a promise.
[src:javascript/async-function] If the return value of an async function is not explicitly a promise, it will be implicitly wrapped in a promise.
[src:javascript/async-function] Note that even though the return value of an async function behaves as if it's wrapped in a `Promise.resolve`, they are not equivalent.
[src:javascript/async-function] An async function will return a different *reference*, whereas `Promise.resolve` returns the same reference if the given value is a promise.
[src:javascript/async-function] It can be a problem when you want to check the equality of a promise and a return value of an async function.
[src:javascript/async-function] The body of an async function can be thought of as being split by zero or more await expressions.
[src:javascript/async-function] Top-level code, up to and including the first await expression (if there is one), is run synchronously.
[src:javascript/async-function] In this way, an async function without an await expression will run synchronously.
[src:javascript/async-function] If there is an await expression inside the function body, however, the async function will always complete asynchronously.
[src:javascript/async-function] Code after each await expression can be thought of as existing in a `.then` callback.
[src:javascript/async-function] In this way a promise chain is progressively constructed with each reentrant step through the function.
[src:javascript/async-function] The return value forms the final link in the chain.
[src:javascript/async-function] In the following example, we successively await two promises.
[src:javascript/async-function] Progress moves through function `foo` in three stages.
[src:javascript/async-function] Some time later, when the first promise has either been fulfilled or rejected, control moves back into `foo`.
[src:javascript/async-function] The result of the first promise fulfillment (if it was not rejected) is returned from the await expression.
[src:javascript/async-function] Progress continues, and the second await expression is evaluated.
[src:javascript/async-function] Again, progress through `foo` is suspended and control is yielded.
[src:javascript/async-function] Some time later, when the second promise has either been fulfilled or rejected, control re-enters `foo`.
[src:javascript/async-function] The result of the second promise resolution is returned from the second await expression.
[src:javascript/async-function] Control moves to the return expression (if any).
[src:javascript/async-function] The default return value of `undefined` is returned as the resolution value of the current promise.
[src:javascript/async-function] Note how the promise chain is not built-up in one go.
[src:javascript/async-function] Instead, the promise chain is constructed in stages as control is successively yielded from and returned to the async function.
[src:javascript/async-function] As a result, we must be mindful of error handling behavior when dealing with concurrent asynchronous operations.
[src:javascript/async-function] For example, in the following code an unhandled promise rejection error will be thrown, even if a `.catch` handler has been configured further along the promise chain.
[src:javascript/async-function] This is because `p2` will not be "wired into" the promise chain until control returns from `p1`.
[src:javascript/async-function] `async function` declarations behave similar to `function` declarations — they are hoisted to the top of their scope and can be called anywhere in their scope, and they can be redeclared only in certain contexts.
[src:javascript/async-function] In `sequentialStart`, execution suspends 2 seconds for the first `await`, and then another second for the second `await`.
[src:javascript/async-function] The second timer is not created until the first has already fired, so the code finishes after 3 seconds.
[src:javascript/async-function] In `sequentialWait`, both timers are created and then `await`ed.
[src:javascript/async-function] The timers run concurrently, which means the code finishes in 2 rather than 3 seconds, i.e., the slowest timer.
[src:javascript/async-function] However, the `await` calls still run in series, which means the second `await` will wait for the first one to finish.
[src:javascript/async-function] In this case, the result of the fastest timer is processed after the slowest.
[src:javascript/async-function] If you wish to safely perform other jobs after two or more jobs run concurrently and are complete, you must await a call to `Promise.all()` or `Promise.allSettled()` before that job.
[src:javascript/async-function] In `sequentialWait`, if promise `fast` rejects before promise `slow` is fulfilled, then an unhandled promise rejection error will be raised, regardless of whether the caller has configured a catch clause.
[src:javascript/async-function] In `concurrent1`, `Promise.all` wires up the promise chain in one go, meaning that the operation will fail-fast regardless of the order of rejection of the promises, and the error will always occur within the configured promise chain, enabling it to be caught in the normal way.
[src:javascript/async-function] An API that returns a `Promise` will result in a promise chain, and it splits the function into many parts.
[src:javascript/async-function] In the two rewritten versions, notice there is no `await` statement after the `return` keyword, although that would be valid too: The return value of an async function is implicitly wrapped in `Promise.resolve` - if it's not already a promise itself (as in the examples).
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] JavaScript supports a compact set of statements, specifically control flow statements, that you can use to incorporate a great deal of interactivity in your application.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] This chapter provides an overview of these statements.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] The JavaScript reference contains exhaustive details about the statements in this chapter.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] The semicolon (`;`) character is used to separate statements in JavaScript code.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] Any JavaScript expression is also a statement.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] See Expressions and operators for complete information about expressions.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] The most basic statement is a *block statement*, which is used to group statements.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] Block statements are commonly used with control flow statements (`if`, `for`, `while`).
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] Here, `{ x++; }` is the block statement.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] This outputs `2` because the `var x` statement within the block is in the same scope as the `var x` statement before the block.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] This scoping effect can be mitigated by using `let` or `const`.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] A conditional statement is a set of commands that executes if a specified condition is true.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] JavaScript supports two conditional statements: `if...else` and `switch`.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] Use the `if` statement to execute a statement if a logical condition is `true`.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] Use the optional `else` clause to execute a statement if the condition is `false`.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] Here, the `condition` can be any expression that evaluates to `true` or `false`.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] If `condition` evaluates to `true`, `statement1` is executed.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] `statement1` and `statement2` can be any statement, including further nested `if` statements.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] In the case of multiple conditions, only the first logical condition which evaluates to `true` will be executed.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] To execute multiple statements, group them within a block statement (`{ /* … */ }`).
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] However, in the rare case you find yourself wanting to do something like that, the `while` documentation has a Using an assignment as a condition section with guidance on a general best-practice syntax you should know about and follow.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] All other values—including all objects—evaluate to `true` when passed to a conditional statement.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] In the following example, the function `checkData` returns `true` if the number of characters in a `Text` object is three.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] Otherwise, it displays an alert and returns `false`.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] A `switch` statement allows a program to evaluate an expression and attempt to match the expression's value to a `case` label.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] If a match is found, the program executes the associated statement.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] The optional `break` statement associated with each `case` clause ensures that the program breaks out of `switch` once the matched statement is executed, and then continues execution at the statement following `switch`.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] If `break` is omitted, the program continues execution inside the `switch` statement (and will execute statements under the next `case`, and so on).
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] In the following example, if `fruitType` evaluates to `"Bananas"`, the program matches the value with `case "Bananas"` and executes the associated statement.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] When `break` is encountered, the program exits the `switch` and continues execution from the statement following `switch`.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] If `break` were omitted, the statement for `case "Cherries"` would also be executed.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] You can throw exceptions using the `throw` statement and handle them using the `try...catch` statements.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] Just about any object can be thrown in JavaScript.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] Nevertheless, not all thrown objects are created equal.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] Use the `throw` statement to throw an exception.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] You may throw any expression, not just expressions of a specific type.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] The `try...catch` statement marks a block of statements to try, and specifies one or more responses should an exception be thrown.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] If an exception is thrown, the `try...catch` statement catches it.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] The `try...catch` statement consists of a `try` block, which contains one or more statements, and a `catch` block, containing statements that specify what to do if an exception is thrown in the `try` block.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] In other words, you want the `try` block to succeed—but if it does not, you want control to pass to the `catch` block.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] If any statement within the `try` block (or in a function called from within the `try` block) throws an exception, control *immediately* shifts to the `catch` block.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] If no exception is thrown in the `try` block, the `catch` block is skipped.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] The `finally` block executes after the `try` and `catch` blocks execute but before the statements following the `try...catch` statement.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] The following example uses a `try...catch` statement.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] The example calls a function that retrieves a month name from an array based on the value passed to the function.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] If the value does not correspond to a month number (`1` – `12`), an exception is thrown with the value `'Invalid month code'` and the statements in the `catch` block set the `monthName` variable to `'unknown'`.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] You can use a `catch` block to handle all exceptions that may be generated in the `try` block.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] The `catch` block specifies an identifier (`exception` in the preceding syntax) that holds the value specified by the `throw` statement.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] You can use this identifier to get information about the exception that was thrown.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] JavaScript creates this identifier when the `catch` block is entered.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] The identifier lasts only for the duration of the `catch` block.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] Once the `catch` block finishes executing, the identifier no longer exists.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] For example, the following code throws an exception.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] When the exception occurs, control transfers to the `catch` block.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] The `finally` block contains statements to be executed *after* the `try` and `catch` blocks execute.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] Additionally, the `finally` block executes *before* the code that follows the `try...catch...finally` statement.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] It is also important to note that the `finally` block will execute *whether or not* an exception is thrown.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] If an exception is thrown, however, the statements in the `finally` block execute even if no `catch` block handles the exception that was thrown.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] You can use the `finally` block to make your script fail gracefully when an exception occurs.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] For example, you may need to release a resource that your script has tied up.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] The following example opens a file and then executes statements that use the file.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] (Server-side JavaScript allows you to access files.) If an exception is thrown while the file is open, the `finally` block closes the file before the script fails.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] Using `finally` here *ensures* that the file is never left open, even if an error occurs.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] You can nest one or more `try...catch` statements.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] 2. the enclosing `try...catch` statement's `catch` block is checked for a match.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] For more information, see nested try-blocks on the `try...catch` reference page.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] Depending on the type of error, you may be able to use the `name` and `message` properties to get a more refined message.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] The `name` property provides the general class of `Error` (such as `DOMException` or `Error`), while `message` generally provides a more succinct message than one would get by converting the error object to a string.
[src:javascript/control-flow-and-error-handling] If you are throwing your own exceptions, in order to take advantage of these properties (such as if your `catch` block doesn't discriminate between your own exceptions and system ones), you can use the `Error` constructor.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] This chapter describes JavaScript's expressions and operators, including assignment, comparison, arithmetic, bitwise, logical, string, ternary and more.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] At a high level, an *expression* is a valid unit of code that resolves to a value.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] There are two types of expressions: those that have side effects (such as assigning values) and those that purely *evaluate*.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The expression `x = 7` is an example of the first type.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] This expression uses the `=` *operator* to assign the value seven to the variable `x`.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The expression `3 + 4` is an example of the second type.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] This expression uses the `+` operator to add `3` and `4` together and produces a value, `7`.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] However, if it's not eventually part of a bigger construct (for example, a variable declaration like `const z = 3 + 4`), its result will be immediately discarded — this is usually a programmer mistake because the evaluation doesn't produce any effects.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] As the examples above also illustrate, all complex expressions are joined by *operators*, such as `=` and `+`.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] These operators join operands either formed by higher-precedence operators or one of the basic expressions.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] A complete and detailed list of operators and expressions is also available in the reference.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The *precedence* of operators determines the order they are applied when evaluating an expression.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] Despite `*` and `+` coming in different orders, both expressions would result in `7` because `*` has precedence over `+`, so the `*`-joined expression will always be evaluated first.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] You can override operator precedence by using parentheses (which creates a grouped expression — the basic expression).
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] To see a complete table of operator precedence as well as various caveats, see the Operator Precedence Reference page.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] JavaScript has both *binary* and *unary* operators, and one special ternary operator, the conditional operator.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] This form is called an *infix* binary operator, because the operator is placed between two operands.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] All binary operators in JavaScript are infix.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The `operator operand` form is called a *prefix* unary operator, and the `operand operator` form is called a *postfix* unary operator.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] `++` and `--` are the only postfix operators in JavaScript — all other operators, like `!`, `typeof`, etc. are prefix.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] An assignment operator assigns a value to its left operand based on the value of its right operand.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The simple assignment operator is equal (`=`), which assigns the value of its right operand to its left operand.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] That is, `x = f()` is an assignment expression that assigns the value of `f()` to `x`.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] If an expression evaluates to an object, then the left-hand side of an assignment expression may make assignments to properties of that expression.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] For more information about objects, read Working with Objects.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] In strict mode, the code above throws, because one cannot assign properties to primitives.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] It is an error to assign values to unmodifiable properties or to properties of an expression without properties (`null` or `undefined`).
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] For more complex assignments, the destructuring syntax is a JavaScript expression that makes it possible to extract data from arrays or objects using a syntax that mirrors the construction of array and object literals.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] In general, assignments are used within a variable declaration (i.e., with `const`, `let`, or `var`) or as standalone statements.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] However, like other expressions, assignment expressions like `x = f()` evaluate into a result value.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] Although this result value is usually not used, it can then be used by another expression.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] Chaining assignments or nesting assignments in other expressions can result in surprising behavior.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] For this reason, some JavaScript style guides discourage chaining or nesting assignments.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] Nevertheless, assignment chaining and nesting may occur sometimes, so it is important to be able to understand how they work.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] By chaining or nesting an assignment expression, its result can itself be assigned to another variable.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] It can be logged, it can be put inside an array literal or function call, and so on.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The evaluation result matches the expression to the right of the `=` sign in the "Meaning" column of the table above.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] That means that `x = f()` evaluates into whatever `f()`'s result is, `x += f()` evaluates into the resulting sum `x + f()`, `x **= f()` evaluates into the resulting power `x ** f()`, and so on.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] In the case of logical assignments, `x &&= f()`, `x ||= f()`, and `x ??= f()`, the return value is that of the logical operation without the assignment, so `x && f()`, `x || f()`, and `x ?? f()`, respectively.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] When chaining these expressions without parentheses or other grouping operators like array literals, the assignment expressions are **grouped right to left** (they are right-associative), but they are **evaluated left to right**.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] Note that, for all assignment operators other than `=` itself, the resulting values are always based on the operands' values *before* the operation.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] `y = x = f()` is equivalent to `y = (x = f())`, because the assignment operator `=` is right-associative.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The assignment expression `x = f()` starts to evaluate.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The function call `f()` prints "F!" to the console and then evaluates to the number `2`.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] That `2` result from `f()` is assigned to `x`.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The assignment expression `x = f()` has now finished evaluating; its result is the new value of `x`, which is `2`.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] That `2` result in turn is also assigned to `y`.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The assignment expression `y = x = f()` has now finished evaluating; its result is the new value of `y` – which happens to be `2`.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] `x` and `y` are assigned to `2`, and the console has printed "F!".
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The inner array literal `[ f(), x = g() ]` starts to evaluate.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The assignment expression `x = g()` starts to evaluate.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The function call `g()` prints "G!" to the console and then evaluates to the number `3`.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] That `3` result from `g()` is assigned to `x`.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The assignment expression `x = g()` has now finished evaluating; its result is the new value of `x`, which is `3`.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] That `3` result becomes the next element in the inner array literal (after the `2` from the `f()`).
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The inner array literal `[ f(), x = g() ]` has now finished evaluating; its result is an array with two values: `[ 2, 3 ]`.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] That `[ 2, 3 ]` array is now assigned to `y`.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The assignment expression `y = [ f(), x = g() ]` has now finished evaluating; its result is the new value of `y` – which happens to be `[ 2, 3 ]`.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] `x` is now assigned to `3`, `y` is now assigned to `[ 2, 3 ]`, and the console has printed "F!" then "G!".
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] `x[f()] = g()` also evaluates from left to right.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] (This example assumes that `x` is already assigned to some object.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] Then the function call `f()` prints "F!" to the console and then evaluates to the number `2`.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The `x[f()]` property access on this assignment has now finished evaluating; its result is a variable property reference: `x[2]`.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] Then the function call `g()` prints "G!" to the console and then evaluates to the number `3`.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The assignment expression `x[f()] = g()` has now finished evaluating; its result is the new value of `x[2]` – which happens to be `3`.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] `x[2]` is now assigned to `3`, and the console has printed "F!" then "G!".
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] For this reason, chaining assignments in the same statement is discouraged.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] In particular, putting a variable chain in a `const`, `let`, or `var` statement often does *not* work.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] Only the outermost/leftmost variable would get declared; other variables within the assignment chain are *not* declared by the `const`/`let`/`var` statement.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] This statement seemingly declares the variables `x`, `y`, and `z`.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] However, it only actually declares the variable `z`.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] `y` and `x` are either invalid references to nonexistent variables (in strict mode) or, worse, would implicitly create global variables for `x` and `y` in sloppy mode.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] A comparison operator compares its operands and returns a logical value based on whether the comparison is true.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The operands can be numerical, string, logical, or object values.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] Strings are compared based on standard lexicographical ordering, using Unicode values.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] In most cases, if the two operands are not of the same type, JavaScript attempts to convert them to an appropriate type for the comparison.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] This behavior generally results in comparing the operands numerically.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The sole exceptions to type conversion within comparisons involve the `===` and `!==` operators, which perform strict equality and inequality comparisons.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] These operators do not attempt to convert the operands to compatible types before checking equality.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] An arithmetic operator takes numerical values (either literals or variables) as their operands and returns a single numerical value.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The standard arithmetic operators are addition (`+`), subtraction (`-`), multiplication (`*`), and division (`/`).
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] These operators work as they do in most other programming languages when used with floating point numbers (in particular, note that division by zero produces `Infinity`).
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] A bitwise operator treats their operands as a set of 32 bits (zeros and ones), rather than as decimal, hexadecimal, or octal numbers.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] For example, the decimal number nine has a binary representation of 1001.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] Bitwise operators perform their operations on such binary representations, but they return standard JavaScript numerical values.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The following table summarizes JavaScript's bitwise operators.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] For example, the binary representation of nine is 1001, and the binary representation of fifteen is 1111.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] Note that all 32 bits are inverted using the Bitwise NOT operator, and that values with the most significant (left-most) bit set to 1 represent negative numbers (two's-complement representation).
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] `~x` evaluates to the same value that `-x - 1` evaluates to.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The bitwise shift operators take two operands: the first is a quantity to be shifted, and the second specifies the number of bit positions by which the first operand is to be shifted.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The direction of the shift operation is controlled by the operator used.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] Shift operators convert their operands to thirty-two-bit integers and return a result of either type `Number` or `BigInt`: specifically, if the type of the left operand is `BigInt`, they return `BigInt`; otherwise, they return `Number`.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The shift operators are listed in the following table.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] Logical operators are typically used with Boolean (logical) values; when they are, they return a Boolean value.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] However, the `&&`, `||`, and `??` operators actually return the value of one of the specified operands, so if these operators are used with non-Boolean values, they may return a non-Boolean value.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] As such, they are more adequately called "value selection operators".
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The logical operators are described in the following table.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] Examples of expressions that can be converted to `false` are those that evaluate to `null`, `0`, `0n`, `NaN`, the empty string (`""`), or `undefined`.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The following code shows examples of the `&&` (logical AND) operator.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The following code shows examples of the `||` (logical OR) operator.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The following code shows examples of the `??` (nullish coalescing) operator.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] Note how `??` works like `||`, but it only returns the second expression when the first one is "nullish", i.e., `null` or `undefined`.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] `??` is a better alternative than `||` for setting defaults for values that might be `null` or `undefined`, in particular when values like `''` or `0` are valid values and the default should not apply.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The following code shows examples of the `!` (logical NOT) operator.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The rules of logic guarantee that these evaluations are always correct.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] Note that the *anything* part of the above expressions is not evaluated, so any side effects of doing so do not take effect.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] Most operators that can be used between numbers can be used between `BigInt` values as well.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] One exception is unsigned right shift (`>>>`), which is not defined for BigInt values.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] This is because a BigInt does not have a fixed width, so technically it does not have a "highest bit".
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] BigInts and numbers are not mutually replaceable — you cannot mix them in calculations.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] This is because BigInt is neither a subset nor a superset of numbers.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] BigInts have higher precision than numbers when representing large integers, but cannot represent decimals, so implicit conversion on either side might lose precision.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] Use explicit conversion to signal whether you wish the operation to be a number operation or a BigInt one.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] In addition to the comparison operators, which can be used on string values, the concatenation operator (+) concatenates two string values together, returning another string that is the union of the two operand strings.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The shorthand assignment operator `+=` can also be used to concatenate strings.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The conditional operator is the only JavaScript operator that takes three operands.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The operator can have one of two values based on a condition.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] If `condition` is true, the operator has the value of `val1`.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] You can use the conditional operator anywhere you would use a standard operator.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] This statement assigns the value "adult" to the variable `status` if `age` is eighteen or more.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] Otherwise, it assigns the value "minor" to `status`.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The comma operator (`,`) evaluates both of its operands and returns the value of the last operand.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] This operator is primarily used inside a `for` loop, to allow multiple variables to be updated each time through the loop.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] It is regarded bad style to use it elsewhere, when it is not necessary.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] Often two separate statements can and should be used instead.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] For example, if `a` is a 2-dimensional array with 10 elements on a side, the following code uses the comma operator to update two variables at once.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] A unary operation is an operation with only one operand.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The `delete` operator deletes an object's property.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] where `object` is the name of an object, `property` is an existing property, and `propertyKey` is a string or symbol referring to an existing property.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] If the `delete` operator succeeds, it removes the property from the object.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] Trying to access it afterwards will yield `undefined`.
[src:javascript/expressions-and-operators] The `delete` operator returns `true` if the operation is possible; it returns `false` if the operation is not possible.
